T1  - INCENTIVES AND THE COST OF FIRING IN AN EQUILIBRIUM LABOR MARKET MODEL WITH ENDOGENOUS LAYOFFS*
AU  - Wang, Cheng
Y1  - 2013/05/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12002
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 443
EP  - 472
VL  - 54
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12002
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - I study the effects of firing costs in an equilibrium model of the labor market with moral hazard. Layoff is an incentive device, modeled as termination of the optimal long-term contract. When the economy?s stock of firms is fixed, firing costs could reduce layoffs and increase worker welfare. In the long run when firms are free to enter and exit the market, firing costs generate not only lower employment, longer unemployment durations, and lower aggregate output, but also lower welfare for both employed workers and new labor market entrants.
ER  - 

