T1  - AN EMPIRICAL MODEL OF LEARNING UNDER AMBIGUITY: THE CASE OF CLINICAL TRIALS*
AU  - Fernandez,             Jose M.
Y1  - 2013/05/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12006
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 549
EP  - 573
VL  - 54
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12006
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article presents a two-dimensional structural model of learning under ambiguity in the context of clinical trials. Clinical trials offer an ideal environment to study learning under ambiguity. The randomization process found in these studies leaves patients uncertain to their actual group assignment. Therefore, patients cannot immediately attribute changes in health to the experimental drug. The article proposes the use of ?learning instrumental variables? to simultaneously update patients? beliefs of the treatment effect and group assignment. Patient learning is found to be faster when observable side effects are incorporated to account for the uncertainty in group assignment.
ER  - 

